## Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| Wire protocol | Binary format a DB uses to communicate. Postgres wire protocol ≠ SQL. |
| Reverse proxy | Server forwarding client requests to backends. Client doesn't know backends exist. |
| Transparent proxy | Layer 4 proxy. Forwards raw TCP without reading HTTP content. |
| Blue-green deployment | Two identical environments; LB switches traffic for zero-downtime releases + instant rollback. |
| Junction table | Table representing many-to-many via pairs of foreign keys. |
| Multiplexing | Multiple logical streams over one physical connection. HTTP/2, connection pools. |
| HTTP smuggling | Attack on HTTP/1.1 parsing ambiguity. Eliminated by HTTP/2 binary framing. |
| Perceived latency | How fast a system feels. Progressive loading improves it without changing backend speed. |
| Stateless | REST — each request standalone, server remembers nothing. |
| Stateful | gRPC/WebSockets — connection persists, server maintains context. |
| Cursor | DB object for fetching result rows incrementally. Avoids memory blowup on large sets. |
| BIGSERIAL | Postgres auto-incrementing 64-bit integer. Max ~9.2 quintillion. |
| SHA-256 | Hash function. Fixed 256-bit output. Deterministic, one-way. |
| Base62 | URL-safe encoding: a-z, A-Z, 0-9. 8 chars ≈ 218 trillion combos. |
| Hash collision | Two inputs producing the same truncated hash output. |
| Salt | Random value added to input before hashing. Produces different output on retry. |
| 301 redirect | Permanent. Browser caches — you lose analytics. |
| 302 redirect | Temporary. Browser re-requests every time — you keep analytics. |
| LSM Tree | Write-optimized engine. Buffers writes in memory, merges to disk. RocksDB, Cassandra. |

