## Interview Q&A

**Q: Design a URL shortener.**
Table with `(short_code, long_url)`. Hash long URL with SHA-256, Base62 encode, take 8 chars. Insert optimistically — if duplicate primary key, add random salt and retry. Reads do primary key lookup and return 302. Scale reads with replicas via Layer 7 LB. Shard only when master is exhausted.

**Q: Why 302 and not 301?**
301 is cached permanently — users never hit your server again, you lose all click analytics. 302 ensures every click goes through your server for tracking.

**Q: How do you handle hash collisions?**
Insert optimistically. Primary key constraint fires on collision. Add random salt, rehash, retry. Probability is ~1 in 218 trillion — loop runs at most once in practice.

**Q: How would you scale a URL shortener globally?**
Read replicas per region. Layer 7 LB routes GET to nearest replica, POST to master. Eventual consistency is acceptable — users don't click their own link in the same millisecond they created it.

**Q: Layer 4 vs Layer 7 load balancing?**
Layer 4 = TCP level, sees IP/ports, fast, dumb, TLS at backend. Layer 7 = HTTP level, sees method/URL/headers, can route GET to replicas and POST to master, handles TLS termination. Use Layer 7 for web APIs.

**Q: Design the follow relationship.**
Junction table `(source_id, dest_id)`. Index both columns. Inserts are infrequent — B+ tree fine. At scale, cache follower counts in Redis and invalidate on follow/unfollow.

**Q: How would you display the follow button state efficiently?**
Progressive loading — return profile data immediately, async query the follow relationship. Button stays grayed out until async response arrives. Minimizes perceived latency on the most frequent operation.

**Q: When Design 1 vs Design 2 for URL shortener?**
Design 1 for internal/automated (Twitter auto-shortening, user never sees the code, write throughput matters). Design 2 for user-facing products (Bitly) where custom URLs and non-guessable codes matter.

**Q: Tradeoff of a message queue for writes?**
Gain: client never sees failure once request hits server, decouples write speed from DB, natural retry mechanism. Cost: eventual consistency, new infrastructure to maintain (queue + worker processes).
